  series               = {ICEE International Conference on Energy & Environment},
  abstract             = {The main challenge of hydrogen electrolysis is the high costs of the hydrogen production. For a decarbonized energy sector, new investments are needed to drive the shift of CO2 from intensive technologies to sustainable technologies. However, it is not easy for investors to choose these options. Currently green hydrogen project accounts for more than 500 undergoing initiatives around the world and should grow quickly in the coming years. From several feasibility studies, green hydrogen originating from renewable power is technically viable today and is quickly approaching economic competitiveness. The focus is on deployment and learning-by-doing to reduce electrolysers' costs and supply chain logistics. This will require an appropriate funding schemes, mostly led by public sector and in some cases private sector as well. The analysis of the financing structure in Germany, Australia and Brazil shows that the role of the government in this nascent industry is fundamental for its viability. The results of our model ratifies this perception, where the governmental arm acts in an indispensable route for the feasibility of green hydrogen and consequently reduction of the carbon footprint so as to meet the Paris Agreement and the transition to a neutral economy.},
